<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-908-478  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 908 478.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 19 1989 n1186 p11(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hacking law plan draws applause. (The British Law Commission'sproposal to outlaw computer hacking)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nicolle, Lindsay.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The British Law Commission proposes a plan, with an implementationtarget date of 1992, to punish computer hackers and virus writerswith up to five years of imprisonment.andP;  The bill is expected topass before the advent of the common European market, when theneed for secure systems will increase.andP;  The plan has gainedsupport from government offices, the anti-hacking and virus lobbyand the National Computer Users Forum.andP;  The lobby is particularlyconcerned about tampering with safety critical systems, financialand defense networks and personal information databases.andP;  TheEuropean Community is discussing liability in member countries andcould be influenced by France, where hacking has been illegalsince 1985.andP;  The minority against the plan suggest thatimplementation will drive hacking underground.andP;  Proponents,however argue that the law would be a deterrent and an indicatorof socially unacceptable behavior.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer HackersGreat Britain. Law CommissionComputer VirusesGovernment RegulationFraudEuropean CommunityEnglandLegislationComputer Crimes.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>